{
  "doc_id": "690",
  "text": "High doses of folic acid (5 -10 mg/d) have also been shown to improve FMD in coronary-artery disease patients [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] and smokers [CITATION_3] , forearm blood flow, but not arterial elasticity, in smokers [CITATION_4] , and volumetric coronary blood flow in hyperhomocysteinaemic patients with coronary artery disease [CITATION_5] . This effect was shown to be independent of a plasma homocysteine-lowering effect [CITATION_6] . Lower doses of folic acid (e.g. 0·4 mg/d), which are attainable through the diet and result in maximal homocysteine reductions, have no effect on FMD [CITATION_7] [CITATION_8] .",
